Data analysis

fse

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict fse with age, group and time_point (formula: fse ~ 1 + age + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The models total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.70) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.09. The models intercept, corresponding to age = 0, group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 14.28 (S.E. = 2.08, p < .001, 95% CI [10.21, 18.34]). Within this model:

  • The effect of age is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.07, S.E. = 0.04, p = 0.068, 95% CI [-5.14e-03, 0.14]; Std. beta = 0.24, 95% CI [-0.02, 0.50])
  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.26, S.E. = 1.04, p = 0.801, 95% CI [-2.30, 1.78]; Std. beta = -0.06, 95% CI [-0.57, 0.44])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.57, S.E. = 0.81, p = 0.480, 95% CI [-2.17, 1.02]; Std. beta = -0.14, 95% CI [-0.54, 0.25])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 3.33, S.E. = 1.21, p = 0.006, 95% CI [0.95, 5.70]; Std. beta = 0.82, 95% CI [0.23, 1.41])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
